oraModVersion.name: oraModVersion
oraModVersion.description: Description and version number of this installation.

oraModMode.name: oraModMode
oraModMode.description: This object indicates if the Oracle Module is in full-mode or restricted-mode. Restricted-mode is entered, when SystemEDGE 4.0 and higher, fails to find a valid license. Once a valid license has been allocated and set, the module will then transition to fullMode(1)

oramodTtlCPUTIME.name: oramodTtlCPUTIME
oramodTtlCPUTIME.description: CPU time, in seconds, accumulated by Oracle which includes all its core components and instance. Because core components can come and go, the accumulated cpu time can fluctuate therefore making this variable unsuitable as a counter.

oramodTtlPERCENTCPU.name: oramodTtlPERCENTCPU
oramodTtlPERCENTCPU.description: The percentage of CPU utilization, by Oracle, over the last sample interval. Since fractions are not supported by SNMP, the value reported is the percentage multipled by 100. It is the sum of the CPU utilization of all the Oracle core services and components. Its gives a good indication of the CPU resource consumption by the entire Oracle application'

oramodTtlMEMSIZE.name: oramodTtlMEMSIZE
oramodTtlMEMSIZE.description: The combined size of Oracle's text, data, and stack segments in KBytes. It is the summation of the process sizes for all the core Oracle services and optional connectors.

oramodTtlRSS.name: oramodTtlRSS
oramodTtlRSS.description: The real memory (resident set) size of Oracle in KBytes. It is the summation of the process RSS for all the core Oracle services and optional connectors.

oramodTtlPERCENTMEM.name: oramodTtlPERCENTMEM
oramodTtlPERCENTMEM.description: The percentage (0-100) of real memory used by the Oracle Application which includes core services and optional connectors.

oramodTtlTHREADS.name: oramodTtlTHREADS
oramodTtlTHREADS.description: The total number of threads operating within the respective Oracle components as seen by the operating system. Monitoring the number of threads can help with performance tuning resource contention issues that may be brought about by too many threads or can help identify if too few threads have too great of a workload.

oramodTtlINBLKS.name: oramodTtlINBLKS
oramodTtlINBLKS.description: The number of blocks of data input by the processes.

oramodTtlOUTBLKS.name: oramodTtlOUTBLKS
oramodTtlOUTBLKS.description: The number of blocks of data put by the processes.

oramodTtlMSGSSENT.name: oramodTtlMSGSSENT
oramodTtlMSGSSENT.description: The number of messages sent by the processes.

oramodTtlMSGSRCVD.name: oramodTtlMSGSRCVD
oramodTtlMSGSRCVD.description: The number of messages received by the processes.

oramodTtlSYSCALLS.name: oramodTtlSYSCALLS
oramodTtlSYSCALLS.description: The number of system calls invoked by the processes.

oramodTtlMINORPGFLTS.name: oramodTtlMINORPGFLTS
oramodTtlMINORPGFLTS.description: The number of minor page faults incurred by the process. Minor faults do not require I/O to retrieve the page.

oramodTtlMAJORPGFLTS.name: oramodTtlMAJORPGFLTS
oramodTtlMAJORPGFLTS.description: The number of major page faults incurred by the process. Minor faults require I/O to retrieve the page.

oramodTtlNUMSWAPS.name: oramodTtlNUMSWAPS
oramodTtlNUMSWAPS.description: The number of times the processes have been swapped.

oramodTtlVOLCNTX.name: oramodTtlVOLCNTX
oramodTtlVOLCNTX.description: The number of voluntary context switches incurred by the processes. Voluntary contest switches occur when the processor voluntary gives up the CPU (e.g. waiting on I/O).

oramodTtlINVOLCNTX.name: oramodTtlINVOLCNTX
oramodTtlINVOLCNTX.description: The number of involuntary context switches incurred by the processes. An involuntary context switch occurs when the process has executed for the duration of its time quantum and is switched out by the process scheduler.

oramodTtlDISKSIZE.name: oramodTtlDISKSIZE
oramodTtlDISKSIZE.description: The size, in KBytes of the Oracle root directory and all the Database Disk storage areas.

oramodDbCfgTable.name: oramodDbCfgTable
oramodDbCfgTable.description: This table describes the instance names, index numbers and initial startup information.

oramodDbCfgEntry.name: oramodDbCfgEntry
oramodDbCfgEntry.description: An entry in the Oracle Configuration table.

oramodDbCfgVERSION.name: oramodDbCfgVERSION
oramodDbCfgVERSION.description: Description and version of this Oracle installation from v$version

oramodDbCfgHOME.name: oramodDbCfgHOME
oramodDbCfgHOME.description: The Installation Directory for Oracle or ORACLEHOME.

oramodDbCfgBASE.name: oramodDbCfgBASE
oramodDbCfgBASE.description: The Base Directory for Oracle or ORACLEBASE.

oramodDbCfgID.name: oramodDbCfgID
oramodDbCfgID.description: The database ID calculated when the database is created and stored in all file headers (521382036).

oramodDbCfgCRTDT.name: oramodDbCfgCRTDT
oramodDbCfgCRTDT.description: The original creation date and time of the database.

oramodDbCfgLOGMODE.name: oramodDbCfgLOGMODE
oramodDbCfgLOGMODE.description: The Archive log mode: NOARCHIVELOG or ARCHIVELOG.

oramodDbCfgCTRLFILETYPE.name: oramodDbCfgCTRLFILETYPE
oramodDbCfgCTRLFILETYPE.description: Control File Type. Can be the following types : CURRENT,STANDBY,CLONE,BACKUP,CREATED.

oramodDbCfgOPENMODE.name: oramodDbCfgOPENMODE
oramodDbCfgOPENMODE.description: Shows whether the database is set to READ WRITE or READ ONLY (NEW TO 8i.).

oramodDbCfgMAXPROCESS.name: oramodDbCfgMAXPROCESS
oramodDbCfgMAXPROCESS.description: For a multiple-process operation, this parameter specifies the maximum number of user processes that can simultaneously connect to an Oracle server. The PROCESSES parameter is used to derive the SESSIONS INIT.ORA parameter. The default is 50. Typical range 6 - OS/dependent

oramodDbCfgMAXSESSION.name: oramodDbCfgMAXSESSION
oramodDbCfgMAXSESSION.description: Maximum number of User and System Sessions.

oramodDbCfgTIMEDSTATISTICS.name: oramodDbCfgTIMEDSTATISTICS
oramodDbCfgTIMEDSTATISTICS.description: TRUE/FALSE: sets timing on. Should be false for maximum performance.

oramodDbCfgCPUCNT.name: oramodDbCfgCPUCNT
oramodDbCfgCPUCNT.description: The maximum number of CPU's for this instance.

oramodDbCfgSHAREDPOOLSIZE.name: oramodDbCfgSHAREDPOOLSIZE
oramodDbCfgSHAREDPOOLSIZE.description: Shared Pool Size Size in Kbytes. Controls the size of the memory area used for parsing and executing SQL statements. The default is 3.5 Mbytes. Typical Range 300 Kbytes. It is O/S dependent.

oramodDbCfgJAVAPOOLSIZE.name: oramodDbCfgJAVAPOOLSIZE
oramodDbCfgJAVAPOOLSIZE.description: Java Pool Size in Kbytes Default is (20000K)

oramodDbCfgCNTRLFILES.name: oramodDbCfgCNTRLFILES
oramodDbCfgCNTRLFILES.description: Name and path of control files. String of file names.

oramodDbCfgDBBLKBUFF.name: oramodDbCfgDBBLKBUFF
oramodDbCfgDBBLKBUFF.description: Number of Database Block Buffers in blocks. Controls how much memory is available in the buffer cache for data blocks. Default is (26240)

oramodDbCfgDBBLKSIZE.name: oramodDbCfgDBBLKSIZE
oramodDbCfgDBBLKSIZE.description: Size of Database Blocks. O/S dependent

oramodDbCfgSORTAREASIZE.name: oramodDbCfgSORTAREASIZE
oramodDbCfgSORTAREASIZE.description: Maximum Sort Area Size. Controls the amount of memory allocated to each process in the Process Global Area for any sorting activity (for multithreaded server this is allocated in the shared pool). When a process needs more memory than is available for a sort, disk space must be allocated in the temporary tablespace. Tuning is based on the transaction mix of the application. The default (O/S dependent) is adequate for most DB operations.

oramodDbCfgOPENCURSORS.name: oramodDbCfgOPENCURSORS
oramodDbCfgOPENCURSORS.description: Maximum open cursors a single-user process can have at once. Typical Range (1 - 2147483647).

oramodDbCfgTRNSACTNS.name: oramodDbCfgTRNSACTNS
oramodDbCfgTRNSACTNS.description: Maximum number of concurrent transactions allowed at one time.

oramodDbCfgTRNSACTNSPERSEG.name: oramodDbCfgTRNSACTNSPERSEG
oramodDbCfgTRNSACTNSPERSEG.description: Maximum number of concurrent transactions per segment. Default is 30. O/S dependent.

oramodCfgDfTable.name: oramodCfgDfTable
oramodCfgDfTable.description: This table describes the database files for the database.

oramodCfgDfEntry.name: oramodCfgDfEntry
oramodCfgDfEntry.description: An entry in the Oracle v$datafile table.

oramodCfgDfSTATUS.name: oramodCfgDfSTATUS
oramodCfgDfSTATUS.description: Type of file (system or user) and its status. Values: OFFLINE, ONLINE, SYSTEM, RECOVER, SYSOFF(an offline file from the SYSTEM tablespace).

oramodCfgDfENABLED.name: oramodCfgDfENABLED
oramodCfgDfENABLED.description: Describes how accessible the file is from SQL. Can be DISABLED, READ ONLY, READ WRITE and UNKNOWN.

oramodCfgDfUNRCVRBLECHG.name: oramodCfgDfUNRCVRBLECHG
oramodCfgDfUNRCVRBLECHG.description: The last unrecoverbale change number made to this datafile. Always updated when an unrecoverable operation completes.

oramodCfgDfUNRCVRBLETIME.name: oramodCfgDfUNRCVRBLETIME
oramodCfgDfUNRCVRBLETIME.description: The last unrecoverbale change time made to this datafile. Always updated when an unrecoverable operation completes.

oramodCfgDfKBYTES.name: oramodCfgDfKBYTES
oramodCfgDfKBYTES.description: Current size in kbytes; 0 if unaccessible.

oramodCfgDfCRTTIME.name: oramodCfgDfCRTTIME
oramodCfgDfCRTTIME.description: Time at which the datafile was created.

oramodCfgDfBLOCKS.name: oramodCfgDfBLOCKS
oramodCfgDfBLOCKS.description: Current datafile size in blocks; 0 if inaccessible.

oramodCfgDfERROR.name: oramodCfgDfERROR
oramodCfgDfERROR.description: NULL if the header read success. If error must restore.

oramodCfgLfTable.name: oramodCfgLfTable
oramodCfgLfTable.description: This table describes the redo log files locations for each Oracle installation from v$logfile.

oramodCfgLfEntry.name: oramodCfgLfEntry
oramodCfgLfEntry.description: An entry in the Oracle Logfile table.

oramodCfgSgaTable.name: oramodCfgSgaTable
oramodCfgSgaTable.description: This table summarizes the system global area.

oramodCfgSgaEntry.name: oramodCfgSgaEntry
oramodCfgSgaEntry.description: An entry in the Oracle Sga table.

oramodCfgSgaTOTALMEMALLOC.name: oramodCfgSgaTOTALMEMALLOC
oramodCfgSgaTOTALMEMALLOC.description: Total real memory allocated. Summation of values in v$sga.

oramodCfgSgaVARIABLE.name: oramodCfgSgaVARIABLE
oramodCfgSgaVARIABLE.description: Variable Memory allocated in the SGA

oramodCfgSgaDBBUFF.name: oramodCfgSgaDBBUFF
oramodCfgSgaDBBUFF.description: Database buffers allocated in Kbytes. Typical Range is 4 Kbytes - 2 Gbytes.

oramodFootprtTable.description: This table describes the system footprint.

oramodFootprtPERCENTMEM.description: The percentage (0-100) of real memory used by the Oracle Application which includes core services and optional connectors.

oramodFootprtMINORPGFLTS.description: The number of minor page faults incurred by the process. Minor faults do not require I/O to retrieve the page.

oramodFootprtNUMSWAPS.description: The number of times the processes have been swapped.

oramodFootprtHOMESIZE.name: oramodFootprtHOMESIZE
oramodFootprtHOMESIZE.description: The size, in KBytes of the Oracle root directory and all files beneath it.

oramodFootprtDBDISKSIZE.name: oramodFootprtDBDISKSIZE
oramodFootprtDBDISKSIZE.description: The size, in KBytes, of all the Oracle Database disk storage areas. It is a summation of all database files. Summing these components in one location presents an easy and convenient MIB object to poll and self-monitor.

oramodFootprtLASTUPDATE.name: oramodFootprtLASTUPDATE
oramodFootprtLASTUPDATE.description: The time (based on sysUpTime) that the last update of all variables in the table was completed.

oramodFFootprtTable.name: oramodFFootprtTable
oramodFFootprtTable.description: This table describes the system footprint.

oramodFFootprtEntry.name: oramodFFootprtEntry
oramodFFootprtEntry.description: An entry in the Oracle File Footprint table.

oramodMetricsTable.name: oramodMetricsTable
oramodMetricsTable.description: This table describes the database metrics.

oramodMetricsEntry.name: oramodMetricsEntry
oramodMetricsEntry.description: An entry in the Metrics table.

oramodMetricsBCPT.name: oramodMetricsBCPT
oramodMetricsBCPT.description: Block Changes Per Transaction scaled by 100. This ratio measures the amount of DML work that each transaction performs. Creating or dropping indexes impact this value, because changes to index blocks increment it.

oramodMetricsBGR.name: oramodMetricsBGR
oramodMetricsBGR.description: Block Get Rate Per Second scaled by 100. This ratio determines the block get rate per second. It is a basic measurement of the rate at which the application systems reference the database.

oramodMetricsBVPT.name: oramodMetricsBVPT
oramodMetricsBVPT.description: Block Vists Per Transaction scaled by 100. This ratio measures the work database load imposed per transaction. It is a basic measurement of the application workload. If it is moving independently, then this strongly indicates that there has been a change in the application workload.

oramodMetricsCHR.name: oramodMetricsCHR
oramodMetricsCHR.description: Cache Hit Ratio scaled by 100. Measures the effectiveness of the hits against the buffer cache. Whenever Oracle reads data from disk, it places that data into the buffer cache. Data is aged out of the buffer cache using a least recently used algorithm. Oracle looks in the buffer cache first for data requests. If the data is not there, Oracle searches the disk based data files that comprise the database. On most production systems, Oracle should not have to resort to disk reads more than 20% of the time. So, if the buffer cache hit ratio is less than 80%, you should consider increasing the database buffer cache in the System Global Area. This can be done by increasing the value for DBBLOCKBUFFER in the initialization parameter file.

oramodMetricsCR.name: oramodMetricsCR
oramodMetricsCR.description: Call Rate over time. The number of user and recursive calls over time. This ratio measures the work demand rate being placed on the instance from all work sources.

oramodMetricsCPT.name: oramodMetricsCPT
oramodMetricsCPT.description: Calls Per Transaction scaled by 100. The number of database requests per committed transaction. Can be used to detect changes in the application, or in the way in which it is normally used. Ad hoc queries will cause this value to sharply increase.

oramodMetricsCBR.name: oramodMetricsCBR
oramodMetricsCBR.description: Changed Blocks scaled by 100. Measures the balance between queris and data manipulation language (DML) within the database applications. Can be used to detect changes in application usage or indexes.

oramodMetricsCCR.name: oramodMetricsCCR
oramodMetricsCCR.description: Consistent Change Ratio scaled by 100. The ratio of database consistent changes and consistent gets. It measures the extent to which applications are having to exercise the read consistency mechanism. Update and delete operations are subject to read consistency.

oramodMetricsCRR.name: oramodMetricsCRR
oramodMetricsCRR.description: Continued Row Ratio scaled by 100. Measures the space useage of data blocks. Should be close to zero, except in applications handling long LONG columns. If this ratio increases over time, usually PCTFREE has been set too low on one or more tables.

oramodMetricsLCM.name: oramodMetricsLCM
oramodMetricsLCM.description: Library Cache Miss Ratio scaled by 100. The ratio of missed requests and reloads to access library cached objects since instance startup. The library cache is a memory structure containing shared SQL and PL/SQL areas. Monitoring the library cache is important to determine whether or not to resize the shared pool. If this ratio increases over time, then resource useage can be expected to increase. A rising library cache miss ratio may be due to wider use of application functionality causing more SQL statements and stored procedures to be active that had been previously.

oramodMetricsRTUC.name: oramodMetricsRTUC
oramodMetricsRTUC.description: Recursive To User Call Ratio scaled by 100. The ratio of recursive and user or application calls. A change in this ratio can reflect an application change or the need to adjust the size of the shared pool.

oramodMetricsRLSW.name: oramodMetricsRLSW
oramodMetricsRLSW.description: Redo Log Space Wait Ratio scaled by 100. It shows the rate at which failures are occuring in writing to the redo log space and is used to measure memory allocation. If this ratio is greater than 1/5,000, the the redo log buffer should be increased until the redo log space wait ratio stops failing.

oramodMetricsRSR.name: oramodMetricsRSR
oramodMetricsRSR.description: Row Source Ratio scaled by 100. It shows the percentage of total rows retrieved which came from full table scans. If this percentage start to rise above zero, the interpretation of other statistics may need to be reviewed.

oramodMetricsSOR.name: oramodMetricsSOR
oramodMetricsSOR.description: Sort Overflow Ratio scaled by 100. Indicates the number of sorts which are using temporary segments. Under restrictive circumstances when there is a predominance of medium sorts, increasing the sort area size may be effective.

oramodMetricsTRR.name: oramodMetricsTRR
oramodMetricsTRR.description: Transaction Rate Ratio scaled by 100. The rate at which users or applications are committing transactions. If a fall in this value is associated with a rise in the number of connected users or vice versa, an administrator should be concerned. Changes in application structure or work patterns can also distort this figure.

oramodMetricsUCR.name: oramodMetricsUCR
oramodMetricsUCR.description: User Call Rate Ratio scaled by 100. The rate at which client users or applications are requesting sql statements. Measures the work demand rate being posed by client side applications running under the instance. May not be directly comparable across application system version changes where code has been moved from client to server or vice versa.

oramodMetricsUCPP.name: oramodMetricsUCPP
oramodMetricsUCPP.description: User Calls Per Parse Ratio scaled by 100. The ratio of user calls to parse in the shared SQL area. Indicates how well the application is managing its context area. If it changes, then application change is the most likely explanation, but it may indicate the useage patterns are changing and users are moving from one module to another either more frequently or less frequently. Although the shared SQL area makes the maximizing of this ratio less important than with earlier versions of Oracle, it is still possible to reduce resource usage by raising this ratio.

oramodMetricsURR.name: oramodMetricsURR
oramodMetricsURR.description: User Rollback Ratio scaled by 100. The ratio of user or application transaction rollbacks. Indicates the rate at which application transactions are failing. Rolling back a transaction uses significant resources, and would seem to indicate that all of the resources expended in executing the transaction have been wasted.

oramodMetricsSGALCE.name: oramodMetricsSGALCE
oramodMetricsSGALCE.description: Library Cache Efficiency Percentage scaled by 100. The percentage that a SQL statement did not need to be reloaded because it was already in the library cache. This percentage should be 100. If not, try resizing the SHAREDPOOLSIZE in the initialization file.

oramodMetricsSGADDCE.name: oramodMetricsSGADDCE
oramodMetricsSGADDCE.description: Data Dictionary Cache Efficiency Percentage scaled by 100. Shows the ratio of gets to misses within the shared pool. The ratio should be less than 0.1. Various database operations cause the RDBMS to access its system tables. These system tables are stored in the Oracle data dictionary. The objects in the data dictionary are stored in the system tablespace. When the RDBMS needs access to its system tables, the tables are read into the data dictionary cache. Resizing the shared pool can affect this ratio.

oramodMetricsDBTOTALRW.name: oramodMetricsDBTOTALRW
oramodMetricsDBTOTALRW.description: The total number of physical reads and physical writes since instance startup. See individual descriptions below.

oramodMetricsDBBLKCHG.name: oramodMetricsDBBLKCHG
oramodMetricsDBBLKCHG.description: The total number of database block changes. It is incremented each time that a database block is in memory to create a dirty block. This statistic is a rough indication of total database work. Increments at several thousand per second in the largest systems, so this variable is definitely a wraparound candidate.

oramodMetricsDBBLKGET.name: oramodMetricsDBBLKGET
oramodMetricsDBBLKGET.description: The total number of database block gets since instance startup. It is incremented each time the buffer manager is asked for a database block in current mode, regardless of read consistency. This mode is used to locate blocks which are to be updated, and also to access control information such as segment headers. Only if the requested block is not found in Oracle's Buffer cache will a db block get result in physical I/O.

oramodMetricsDBCNSTGET.name: oramodMetricsDBCNSTGET
oramodMetricsDBCNSTGET.description: The total number of consistent gets since instance startup. This value is incremented each time that the Oracle Buffer Manager is requested to locate a database block as part of a read consistent operation (a query). Only if the requested block is not found in Oracle's Buffer Cache will consistent get result in physical I/O. Increments at several thousand per second in the largest systems, so this variable is definitely a wraparound candidate.

oramodMetricsDBPHYSREAD.name: oramodMetricsDBPHYSREAD
oramodMetricsDBPHYSREAD.description: The total number of physical reads since instance startup. It increments each time a DB Block is retrieved from the disk subsystem, but is not necessarily equal to the number of I/O requests made to the host operating system, as multiblock I/O may be used. A physical read can be viewed as an SGA Buffer Cache miss, hampering throughput (contention induction) and CPU (code pathlength) processing. Unlikely to increment at a rate greater than a few hundred per second.

oramodMetricsDBSORTDISK.name: oramodMetricsDBSORTDISK
oramodMetricsDBSORTDISK.description: The total number of database disk sorts since instance startup. It increments for each sort which has to allocate disk work space. Should be zero.

oramodMetricsDBSORTMEM.name: oramodMetricsDBSORTMEM
oramodMetricsDBSORTMEM.description: The total number of database memory sorts since instance startup. It is incremented for each sort which does not require the allocation of work. Unlikely to increment faster than tens per second, except in the largest systems.

oramodMetricsBLKFREEWAIT.name: oramodMetricsBLKFREEWAIT
oramodMetricsBLKFREEWAIT.description: The percent that a request resulted in a wait for a free block. Should be less than 1%. To reduce contention for a table's free list the table must be recreated with a larger value in the FREELISTS storage parameter.

oramodMetricsMTHRDQUEUEWAIT.name: oramodMetricsMTHRDQUEUEWAIT
oramodMetricsMTHRDQUEUEWAIT.description: The number of seconds waited in queue for multi-threaded servers.

oramodMetricsSESSHIWTRMEM.name: oramodMetricsSESSHIWTRMEM
oramodMetricsSESSHIWTRMEM.description: The maximum highwater amount of session memory used.

oramodMetricsSESSCURRMEM.name: oramodMetricsSESSCURRMEM
oramodMetricsSESSCURRMEM.description: The current maximum amount of session memory used.

oramodMetricsSESSHIWTR.name: oramodMetricsSESSHIWTR
oramodMetricsSESSHIWTR.description: The highwater mark for number of sessions.

oramodMetricsUSERCOMMITS.name: oramodMetricsUSERCOMMITS
oramodMetricsUSERCOMMITS.description: Records the number of database transactions successfully completed and records the number of aborted database transactions. In most real world applications, the value is less the 1 per second.

oramodMetricsUSERROLLBACK.name: oramodMetricsUSERROLLBACK
oramodMetricsUSERROLLBACK.description: The number of transactions rolled back since instance startup.

oramodMetricsUSERCALLS.name: oramodMetricsUSERCALLS
oramodMetricsUSERCALLS.description: The number of transactions started since instance startup.

oramodMetricsDBPHYSWRTS.name: oramodMetricsDBPHYSWRTS
oramodMetricsDBPHYSWRTS.description: The total number of physical writes since instance startup. It increments each time a DB Block is written to the disk. All writes are performed either by DBWR or LGWR, two background processes responsible for getting Blocks out of the SGA and back on disk.

oramodMetricsTBLSCANROWS.name: oramodMetricsTBLSCANROWS
oramodMetricsTBLSCANROWS.description: The number of rows retrieved through table scans since instance startup.

oramodMetricsTBLFTCHROWID.name: oramodMetricsTBLFTCHROWID
oramodMetricsTBLFTCHROWID.description: The number of rows retrieved through table fetches by rowid since instance startup.

oramodMetricsTBLFTCHCROW.name: oramodMetricsTBLFTCHCROW
oramodMetricsTBLFTCHCROW.description: The number of rows retrieved through table fetches by continued row since instance startup.

oramodMetricsRECRSVCALLS.name: oramodMetricsRECRSVCALLS
oramodMetricsRECRSVCALLS.description: The number of recursive calls since instance startup.

oramodMetricsCNSTCHGS.name: oramodMetricsCNSTCHGS
oramodMetricsCNSTCHGS.description: The number of consistent changes since instance startup.

oramodMetricsPARSECNT.name: oramodMetricsPARSECNT
oramodMetricsPARSECNT.description: The number of parses since instance startup.

oramodMetricsCPUTM.description: The amount of time taken to work requests.

oramodMetricsLOGFILESWTCH.description: The number of redo log file switches.

oramodMetricsSHUTDOWNPENDING.description: The shutdown status of the database.

oramodMetricsLASTUPDATE.name: oramodMetricsLASTUPDATE

oramodSgaDddAggEntry.description: An entry in the Data Dictionary Aggregate table.

oramodSGAAGGCNT.name: oramodSGAAGGCNT
oramodSGAAGGCNT.description: Total number of entries in the data dictionary cache since instance startup.

oramodSGAAGGUSGE.name: oramodSGAAGGUSGE
oramodSGAAGGUSGE.description: The total number of cache entries with valid data since instance startup.

oramodSGAAGGFIX.name: oramodSGAAGGFIX
oramodSGAAGGFIX.description: The total number of fixed entries in the data dictionary cache since instance startup.

oramodSGAAGGGET.name: oramodSGAAGGGET
oramodSGAAGGGET.description: The total number of information requests since instance startup.

oramodSGAAGGGETMISS.name: oramodSGAAGGGETMISS
oramodSGAAGGGETMISS.description: The total number of informations requests resulting in cache misses since instance startup.

oramodSGAAGGSCAN.name: oramodSGAAGGSCAN
oramodSGAAGGSCAN.description: The total number of scan requests since instance startup.

oramodSGAAGGSCANMISS.name: oramodSGAAGGSCANMISS
oramodSGAAGGSCANMISS.description: The total number of scan requests resulting in misses since instance startup.

oramodSGAAGGSCANCPLT.name: oramodSGAAGGSCANCPLT
oramodSGAAGGSCANCPLT.description: For subordinate entries, the total number of times list was scanned completely since instance startup.

oramodSGAAGGMODS.name: oramodSGAAGGMODS
oramodSGAAGGMODS.description: The total number of inserts, updates, and deletions since instance startup.

oramodSGAAGGFLUSH.name: oramodSGAAGGFLUSH
oramodSGAAGGFLUSH.description: The total number of times flushed to disk since instance startup.

oramodSgaDlciTable.name: oramodSgaDlciTable
oramodSgaDlciTable.description: This table describes the detailed library cache information.

oramodSgaDlciEntry.name: oramodSgaDlciEntry
oramodSgaDlciEntry.description: An entry in the Library Cache table.

oramodSGADLCINAME.name: oramodSGADLCINAME
oramodSGADLCINAME.description: Library Cache Namespace. (SQL AREA, TABLE/PROCEDURE, BODY, TRIGGER, INDEX, CLUSTER, OBJECT, PIPE)

oramodSGADLCIGET.name: oramodSGADLCIGET
oramodSGADLCIGET.description: The total number of request handles to library namespace since instance startup Typical range (0..500,00).

oramodSGADLCIGETHIT.name: oramodSGADLCIGETHIT
oramodSGADLCIGETHIT.description: The total number of times handles are already allocated in the cache. If the handle is not already allocated it is a miss.

oramodSGADLCIGETHITRT.name: oramodSGADLCIGETHITRT
oramodSGADLCIGETHITRT.description: The Get/Hit ratio determines the percentage of parse calls that find a cursor to share. The value is derived from GETHITS divided by GETS. Should be in the high 90s which indicates that most of the handles the system has tried to get are cached.

oramodSGADLCIPIN.name: oramodSGADLCIPIN
oramodSGADLCIPIN.description: The total number of pin requests for objects in the cache since instance startup.

oramodSGADLCIPINHIT.name: oramodSGADLCIPINHIT
oramodSGADLCIPINHIT.description: The number of pin hits or executions of objects that are already allocated and initiated in the cache. Otherwise, it is a miss, and the system has to reallocate and initialize it with data queried from the database or generate the data.

oramodSGADLCIPINHITRT.name: oramodSGADLCIPINHITRT
oramodSGADLCIPINHITRT.description: The ratio of PINHITS to PINS. Values close to 100 indicate that most of the objects the system has tried to pin and access have been cached.

oramodSGADLCIRELOAD.name: oramodSGADLCIRELOAD
oramodSGADLCIRELOAD.description: Number of times a statement had to be reparsed in order to be executed. Statements are reloaded due to aging or invalidation. Should never be more that one percent of PINS. Goal is the have close to zero reloads.

oramodSGADLCIINVALID.name: oramodSGADLCIINVALID
oramodSGADLCIINVALID.description: The number of times that non-persistant library objects (like SQL areas) have been invalidated.

oramodRedoLogBufTable.name: oramodRedoLogBufTable
oramodRedoLogBufTable.description: This table describes the Redo Log information.

oramodRedoLogBufEntry.name: oramodRedoLogBufEntry
oramodRedoLogBufEntry.description: An entry in the Redo Log table.

oramodREDOBLKWRT.name: oramodREDOBLKWRT
oramodREDOBLKWRT.description: The total number of redo blocks written since instance startup.

oramodREDOENTRIES.name: oramodREDOENTRIES
oramodREDOENTRIES.description: The total number of redo entries in the redo log since instance startup.

oramodREDOSIZE.name: oramodREDOSIZE
oramodREDOSIZE.description: The size of the redo log.

oramodREDOSPACERQST.name: oramodREDOSPACERQST
oramodREDOSPACERQST.description: The number of redo log space requests. Should be close to zero. A nonzero value means the the buffer may be too small. Increase the size of the buffer so that processes are not waiting. The INIT.ora parameter LOGBUFFER controls the size of the redo log buffer.

oramodREDOSPACEWAIT.name: oramodREDOSPACEWAIT
oramodREDOSPACEWAIT.description: The total number of redo log space wait time since instance startup

oramodREDOSYNCHWRT.name: oramodREDOSYNCHWRT
oramodREDOSYNCHWRT.description: The total number of redo synch writes since instance startup.

oramodREDOSYNCHTM.name: oramodREDOSYNCHTM
oramodREDOSYNCHTM.description: The amount of redo log synch time.

oramodREDOWASTAGE.name: oramodREDOWASTAGE
oramodREDOWASTAGE.description: The total amount of redo log wastage.

oramodREDORETRIES.name: oramodREDORETRIES
oramodREDORETRIES.description: The total number of redo retries.

oramodREDOLASTUPDATE.name: oramodREDOLASTUPDATE
oramodREDOLASTUPDATE.description: The time (based on sysUpTime) that the last update of all variables in the table was completed.

oramodRollBackTable.name: oramodRollBackTable
oramodRollBackTable.description: This table describes any rollback segments.

oramodRollBackEntry.name: oramodRollBackEntry
oramodRollBackEntry.description: An entry in the rollstat table.

oramodRollBackSEGINDX.name: oramodRollBackSEGINDX
oramodRollBackSEGINDX.description: Undo Segment Number used as an index.

oramodRollBackEXTENTS.name: oramodRollBackEXTENTS
oramodRollBackEXTENTS.description: The total number of Segment Extends since instance startup.

oramodRollBackRSSIZE.name: oramodRollBackRSSIZE
oramodRollBackRSSIZE.description: The size of the Rollback Segment.

oramodRollBackWRITES.name: oramodRollBackWRITES
oramodRollBackWRITES.description: The total number of Segment Writes since instance startup.

oramodRollBackGETS.name: oramodRollBackGETS
oramodRollBackGETS.description: The total number of Rollback Segment Gets since instance startup.

oramodRollBackWAITS.name: oramodRollBackWAITS
oramodRollBackWAITS.description: The total number of Segment Waits since instance startup.

oramodRollBackOPTSIZE.name: oramodRollBackOPTSIZE
oramodRollBackOPTSIZE.description: The Optimal Size of the Rollback Segment. This size should be set based on application usage to minimize space management issues.

oramodRollBackSHRINKS.name: oramodRollBackSHRINKS
oramodRollBackSHRINKS.description: The total number of Rollback Segment Shrinks since instance startup. Rollback Segments shrink back to their optimal size after extends have occurred.

oramodRollBackWRAPS.name: oramodRollBackWRAPS
oramodRollBackWRAPS.description: The total number of Rollback Segment wraps since instance startup. When a transaction's rollback segment entry cannot be stored within a single extent, the entry wraps into a second extent within the rollback segment. If this value is non-zero, try recreating the rollback segments with larger extent sizes.

oramodRollBackEXTENDS.name: oramodRollBackEXTENDS
oramodRollBackEXTENDS.description: Rollback Segment extends. Extensions indicate that the rollback segments are handling larger transactions than they were designed for; and if the entire rollback segment cannot handle a transaction's rollback information, a single extent will not be able to hold it either. Thus, rollback segments that extend will frequently have a high number of wraps.

oramodRollBackAVESHRINK.name: oramodRollBackAVESHRINK
oramodRollBackAVESHRINK.description: The average shrink size of the Rollback Segment since this instance startup.

oramodWaitsEntry.name: oramodWaitsEntry
oramodWaitsEntry.description: An entry in the waits table.

oramodExpSqlEntry.name: oramodExpSqlEntry
oramodExpSqlEntry.description: An entry in the v$sqlarea table.

oramodExpSqlPARSECNT.name: oramodExpSqlPARSECNT
oramodExpSqlPARSECNT.description: Number of Parses. Parsing is the work done by the database to validate the SQL statement and generate the query plan used for execution. When the parse count is close to that of executions for a given statement, you may be continually reparsing that statement. You can reduce parsing by making sure that statements are reused as much as possible in the shared pool. In general, a large number of hard parses indicates that more memory is needed for the shared pool.

oramodTblspEntry.name: oramodTblspEntry
oramodTblspEntry.description: An entry from the dbafreespace table.

oramodTblspLRGEXTENT.name: oramodTblspLRGEXTENT
oramodTblspLRGEXTENT.description: Size in bytes of the largest extent.

oramodTblspSMEXTENT.name: oramodTblspSMEXTENT
oramodTblspSMEXTENT.description: Size in bytes of the smallest extent.

oramodTblspINCREMENTBY.name: oramodTblspINCREMENTBY
oramodTblspINCREMENTBY.description: Size in bytes of the next extent increment.

oramodTblspBYTESCOALSD.name: oramodTblspBYTESCOALSD
oramodTblspBYTESCOALSD.description: The number of free bytes that were coalesed. If this number does not match bytesfree then the tablespace has some extents that can be coalesced.

oramodTblspBYTESFREE.name: oramodTblspBYTESFREE
oramodTblspBYTESFREE.description: The total number of free bytes available.

oramodLockEntry.name: oramodLockEntry
oramodLockEntry.description: An entry from the lock and session tables.

oramodLockOBJECT.name: oramodLockOBJECT
oramodLockOBJECT.description: The name of the locked object.

oramodLockMODE.name: oramodLockMODE
oramodLockMODE.description: Lock Mode held (Null, Row share, Row exclusive, Share, Share row exclusive, Exclusive).

oramodLockCTIME.name: oramodLockCTIME
oramodLockCTIME.description: Time since current mode was granted.

oramodLockBLOCK.name: oramodLockBLOCK
oramodLockBLOCK.description: The lock is blocking another lock.

oramodLatchEntry.name: oramodLatchEntry
oramodLatchEntry.description: An entry from the latch table.

oramodLatchGETS.name: oramodLatchGETS
oramodLatchGETS.description: Latch Gets. Reflects the proportion of times requests for latches are satisfied without waiting. Should be high.

oramodLatchWAITSHOLDING.name: oramodLatchWAITSHOLDING
oramodLatchWAITSHOLDING.description: Latch Immediate Misses. When a session cannot acquire a latch, it goes into active wait and repeatedly trys to acquire the latch impaitiently.

oramodLatchSPINGETS.name: oramodLatchSPINGETS
oramodLatchSPINGETS.description: Latch Spin Gets. Some latch types will lock into a tight loop testing the latch and trying to get it. Spinning uses significant CPU resources. The number of spins depends on the spincount set it the init.ora file. Once the number of spincounts has been reached the prcess will back off and sleep.

oramodBackupEntry.name: oramodBackupEntry
oramodBackupEntry.description: An entry from the backup table.

oramodBackupCHANGENUM.name: oramodBackupCHANGENUM
oramodBackupCHANGENUM.description: The change number of the backup file.

oramodArcDestEntry.name: oramodArcDestEntry
oramodArcDestEntry.description: An entry from the archive destination table.
